Aunty: लोग तो आते थे मिलने उनसे, उनकी ससुराल वाले भी बहुत आते थे। अनुप श्रीवास्तव... श्रीमाताजी के ननद की लड़की जहां ब्याही थी, उनके ननद के घर... ननद की लड़की की ससुराल। बहुत आते थे, श्रीमाताजी बहुत प्यार करती थीं उस फैमिली को। अनुप के फादर... अनुप ऑस्ट्रेलिया में है इस समय। अनुप, अनुप की बहन, दोनों की श्रीमाताजी ने शादी कराई है। तो उनके फादर को बाई... यह दिल्ली ले गए, दिल्ली ले जाकर कि... तो जब उसकी डेथ हुई है उनके फादर की, तो श्रीमाताजी ने उससे बोला, अनुप की बहन से, कि "अपनी मां से जाकर कह दो कि वो मेरे पास बैठे हैं।" आप समझीं मेरी बात ना? मतलब, आफ्टर डेथ... जो उनके अनुप के फादर... उन्होंने अपनी शरण में ले लिया और उन्होंने कन्वे किया यह बात जाकर कह दो। तो उनकी जो अनुप की मां थीं, हमारे घर आई थीं, बहुत सीधी, बहुत सिंपल लेडी।

Interviewer: तकनीकी सहारा लिया और यह सारा मुमकिन हो गया। और अंकल, आंटी, so many thanks, बहुत-बहुत धन्यवाद कि आप लोगों ने इतना समय निकाल के, फोटोज निकाल के एल्बम से, हम लोग के साथ साझा किया। श्रीमाताजी की स्मृतियां लखनऊ में बहुत विशेष हैं।

Aunty: मेरे पिताजी तो जब उन्होंने फर्स्ट टाइम श्रीमाताजी को देखा... उन्होंने जब देखा तो वो कहने लगे कि... इतना ग्लो उनके चेहरे पर था! वो तो उस टाइम रहे होंगे 70 इयर्स के, हमारे पापा। इतना ग्लो था कि वो पीछे बैठे थे और आगे आए देखने के लिए। हमसे बोले, "तुम्हारी माताजी के चेहरे पर तो बहुत ग्लो है! मैं तो पास से देखने गया।"

Interviewer: Amazing, amazing! तो शब्द नहीं है। इस तरीके से उन्होंने सब संभव किया है और अपने आशीर्वाद से हम सबको रखा है। बहुत-बहुत शुक्रिया, बहुत-बहुत धन्यवाद, Uncle Dr. Prakash and Dr. Veena. Thank you, all friends.

Aunty: थैंक यू, श्रीमाताजी की वजह से हम सभी इकट्ठे हुए।

All: थैंक यू। जय श्रीमाताजी। जय श्रीमाताजी।

Translation

Jai Shri Mataji. Dr. Jay Prakash Uncle and Aunty, and Dr. Anand Narayan, Jai Shri Mataji.

Shri Mataji's connection with Lucknow is very, very dear to us all. I'm so thankful that you've been able to take this time and join us. So, Dr. Jay Prakash Uncle and Aunty, would you like to please start this session by sharing when was the first time you met Shri Mataji and what was it like?

I met Shri Mataji on December 19th at Ganpatipule. We were both there, and there was a very amazing moment during a gift distribution. When my number came out...

...कि कब खरीदी, कब उनको दी, और मुझे कि मैंने इस्तेमाल ही नहीं की। यह बात है '91 की, माई के बाद। तब से मेरी जो है, सिगरेट छूटी, पान छूटा, तम्बाकू छूटी।

I was challenging Shri Mataji in my mind. Shri Mataji knew what I wanted, and as she directed, I just kept doing the work.

Interviewer: Very nice, that’s a wonderful experience, Uncle. And it's not easy to quit tobacco, cigarettes, and all these addictions so quickly. So your realization and the experience of vibrations was in December 1990 in Ganpatipule, and in May, your addiction was gone on its own because you challenged Shri Mataji in your mind. Wow, wow, wow. Aunty, when did you meet her for the first time?

I also met her in 1990. But from a very young age, I used to worship Radha-Krishna, and I was especially devoted to Radha Ji. I always felt that I would find a guru, and it had to be a lady guru. I had a good practice, and patients would come. Sometimes ladies would try to pull me towards their own paths, but I refused everyone. When Raji Bhaiya told us about Sahaja Yoga, I understood a little. For me, it was an unbreakable connection.

At that program, all the ladies were given many gifts, but I was only given a photo. This was in December of 1990. I hadn't fully come into Sahaj at that time; it was just the beginning, so I was a little... Anyway, Shri Mataji told me, "You do meditation, move forward, and ascend." I understood a little. After that, we came back. As I told you, there were problems in life—my father-in-law was there, it was a joint family—but with unwavering faith, we kept moving forward. Shri Mataji’s grace was always there.

I’ll tell you one story which is very beautiful. I used to love Shri Mataji’s eyes. They were so beautiful to me. Shri Mataji was speaking, and I was just looking at her eyes. I was thinking, "These are black, but they aren't brown." Just then, Shri Mataji got up from her chair and came and stood right next to me. I was completely stunned. She showed me her divine form (swarup).

Interviewer: Where did this happen?

This was also in Ganpatipule. This must have been in '91, the next year, as we started going regularly after that. Yes, it was in 1991.

Interviewer: She is the Adi Shakti, absolutely, there is no doubt about it. Today, we have another guest with us, Dr. Anand Narayan. Dr. Anand Narayan is the son of Dr. Avdhesh Narayan, who was our childhood neighbor. The house that Shri Mataji had built, our small connection to it is that his father was our family doctor when my brother Shailesh and I were very young. We had moved to Lucknow from Calcutta and were in Nirala Nagar.

His father used to give us a red liquid, and just one sip of it would cure whatever problem we had. I still remember from my childhood, my parents talking and wondering, "What does Dr. Avdhesh put in this? One sip and you're fine."

Welcome, and please share your experiences.

Dr. Anand Narayan: Thank you so much, Sushmita ji, and Doctor Uncle and Aunty. It’s been a pleasure talking about Mataji. We have very vivid memories of her throughout our entire childhood. My association with her dates back to 1972. I remember in the evening, Sir C.P. Srivastava was getting his daughter married on P.D. Road. He was the chairman of the Shipping Corporation of India. We went from Lucknow to attend the wedding. I was very young, and Sir C.P. Srivastava used to carry me in his arms and walk around. That is my first and oldest recall. And to think of him being in such a powerful position, such a senior civil servant, and at that moment...

Everything is still very clear in my memory. Daddy tells me that in 1963 or '64, when our house was built at number 33, the plot next to it, number 34, was empty. So, he wrote a postcard—which probably cost four annas at the time—and sent it to Sir C.P., who was posted in London. He wrote, "I have had my house constructed, and I request you to also have yours constructed." That postcard reached him, and he made the program, visited Lucknow, and had the entire house built.

It was exactly like ours. He had a two-bedroom portion on the first floor, on the side facing his plot, opened for her. The landlord let her stay there; there were no tenancy issues in those days. It was a godsend. And in one of her earlier biographies, it's mentioned that the Kundalini awakening she had happened in that very room. That room is still one of our treasured places.

It’s a room where, and I have been observing this for many years, bachelors or spinsters who came to stay would get married. It became very famous that if someone wasn't getting married, they should rent that room. It has happened with almost seven or eight tenants, and I have seen it myself. Even now, when you go into that room, you feel so much peace. It’s east-facing, so the first rays of the sun come in there. It has an aura of its own. We have many rooms, but the atmosphere in that one is different. My wife and I stayed in that room for one year after our marriage.

Shri Mataji was very fond of my father. As you said, she had her own remedies. Whenever there was any issue, she would say, "Avdhesh, I have this problem or that problem." She even stayed at the Clark's [Hotel] a couple of times. Daddy would go before his clinic started, at 8 in the morning, to take us children to meet her quickly. As soon as she found out Avdhesh had come, she would say, "Send him in, he must have to get to his clinic." She would always make my daddy sit right next to her. My mother cooks non-veg food very well, as is common in Kayastha families, so she would often come over.

In 1984, she stayed with us for about seven days for my brother's wedding, which was on December 8th. She arrived around the 5th or 6th and stayed until the 12th or 13th. Her disciples also came—there were five of them, some from Australia and one from New Zealand, along with a couple of Indians. They all stayed at our home. In those days, Lucknow wasn't as plush, and things were simple. Her bed was set up in a separate room, but there was no fuss that she had some special requirements.

In those days, weddings weren't one-day events; they lasted for seven days with various ceremonies and meals three times a day. All her disciples, the Australians and New Zealanders, were absolutely mesmerized. They were so Indian, more Indian than us. They participated in everything so simply. Recalling it today, we didn't provide them with many facilities, but still, they were so comfortable and happy attending the wedding and everything.

As I told you, my brother's wedding was on December 8th, 1984. Around the 25th or 26th of November, my mom was talking to him, asking, "What will you wear? You still haven't decided. Your three-piece suit is ready." He said, "I want to wear a sherwani." Around the 29th or 30th of November, my elder brother told my mother he wanted to wear one. At that time, Shri Mataji was touring China. She called up when Daddy called to remind her of the invitation for December 8th. She said, "Not only will I come, but I have a gift for him."

And before she arrived, she sent a gift for him. It was a beautiful, silken, golden-colored fabric for a sherwani—I have never seen fabric like that since. It was made into an achkan. She also sent a golden pocket watch with beautiful carving on it. She was so happy. We were totally astounded. How in the world did she come to know that my brother wanted to wear an achkan, and a silken one at that? In those days, everyone wore suits. I remember this clearly from 1984; I was in class 12.

Then, in March 1985, my sister got married. She came again and stayed with us. She didn't have as many people traveling with her then. She stayed one day with us, and the rest of the time her booking was at Clark's. She attended the wedding and enjoyed it a lot. Her granddaughters also came—Sadhna Didi's daughter and Kalpana Didi's daughter. Romel, Sadhna Didi's husband, was from a royal family in Arrah, Bihar. Kalpana Didi's marriage was arranged by Daddy. Her husband, P.K. Srivastava, was the physics topper at Lucknow University at that time. Sir C.P. Srivastava and Mataji must have asked, and my father knew of him through a patient who lived in the Ganeshganj area. Daddy told them about this boy, the gold medalist, and he initiated the proposal. We have such vivid memories.

Interviewer: A few days ago, Uncle Brijesh Kapoor was telling us that he and Prabhat ji were next-door neighbors and best friends. And here you are telling the story of how Shri Mataji connects people. It is just so amazing.

Dr. Anand Narayan: I have been to her ashram in Vashi also, and I attended one of the mega-congregations organized by Sahaj Yogis in Bombay at Shivaji Park. It's a major park where Sachin Tendulkar and Gavaskar grew up playing. Her program was there, and a huge crowd was listening in pin-drop silence with rapt attention. When her cavalcade left afterward... I still remember, as her car was going by, I was sitting next to her on the dais, and people were doing this [gestures feeling vibrations]. I wondered what it was and even did it myself, but I didn't feel anything. These are very vivid memories.

Interviewer: Which year was this?

Dr. Anand Narayan: This would be around '91 or '92.

Interviewer: Coming back to Uncle Jay Prakash and Aunty, please tell us your good name.

Aunty: My name is Veena.

Interviewer: We will call you Aunty and Uncle.

Aunty: Of course, of course.

Interviewer: So, as Dr. Anand Bhaiya was just describing the program in Dadar, that must have been after your Ganpatipule experience?

Dr. Anand Narayan: She was a very frequent traveler and a very, very active guru. She was always so much surrounded by her disciples and her fans that even for a small function... I don't remember if it was before Holi or Saraswati Puja, but there was such a beautiful celebration with singing, music, and thousands of people sitting, doing bhajans.

One time, Dr. D.Y. Patil, who was a very senior Maharashtra politician and I think later became the Governor of Tripura, was very close to my father. He asked my father, "Please bring Mataji to my home." You won't believe it, we didn't think Mataji would agree because she had such a busy schedule. But both Sir C.P. Srivastava and Mataji Nirmala came to his sea-facing home. He had a sprawling, multi-billionaire flat—you can't get better than that in Mumbai, a beautiful location with the Arabian Sea right in front.

Daddy asked her, and she never refused him, so she agreed. This was a personal dinner. Only she, Mataji, was there, Sir C.P. Srivastava, Dr. D.Y. Patil, his wife, my mother, and myself. Just a few of us. And I still remember, on Dr. D.Y. Patil's dining table, golden plates were laid out, with golden glasses and bowls. And he, such a senior politician, kept sitting on the floor. He sat there pressing Mataji Nirmala's feet the entire time she was talking—just normal conversation, with a little spirituality mixed in. We were sitting next to the sofa, but he remained on the floor, continuously pressing her feet. These are the memories of her as a person. She was a very, very practical-minded spiritual guru.

Aunty: That practicality Shri Mataji taught us, we also try to emulate it as much as possible. We have also been to her house in Nirala Nagar to welcome her.

You felt her eyes were brown, but they were pure, pristine black. And she had a very, very penetrating gaze. When she looked at you, it felt as if her gaze could see right through your mind. It took effort for us to even look into her eyes. That was the first time, and I was in my 40s then. I was very busy with my practice, so it was a different time.

Once, Shri Mataji came to Clark's Avadh. She stayed there for two days. We did our best to decorate the place. It might not have been up to her standards, but we did our best. My friend put up artificial flowers and sprayed a lot of perfume. As soon as Shri Mataji came, she said, "It smells so fragrant here. Have you all sprayed scent?"

People came and went. I was very tired from household duties and managing Shri Mataji's arrival. I was sitting by the side with my hands folded. I had a fever. She was coming from a distance down the long hotel suite corridor. And just like that—it was a miracle—as she came closer, my fever started to subside. It felt like she was pulling it away from me.

Interviewer: This was in December 1995, during the India tour.

Aunty: Yes, during the India tour. This is a big example of how ego rises and how it is cured. As she came closer, my fever disappeared. When she came and sat on the chair we had arranged for her at the public program, she kept moving her feet, here and there. Then she said to someone, "Call the leader's wife." I was at the gate of Clark's Avadh. I came running. I said, "Shri Mataji, you called for me?" She said, "Who made these cushions for my feet?"

They were placed under her feet. She said, "Bring the old ones." Later I understood. The person from whom we had them made was the kind who scolds and bosses people around, so she was scolding the cushions. Right then, I called a Sahaja Yogi brother from home, and he brought different cushions, which we placed for her. What can I say about her? Everything is a miracle. So this was in '95.

This is from '92. This was the first time we did her aarti. We didn't know anything—what to put in the thali, how to do the aarti. A Sahaja Yogi brother, Dr. Verma, took me to Hazratganj on his scooter. We bought a thali, then put camphor in it...

[Shows photo]

Interviewer: Bring it a little closer to the camera, please. A little higher, Uncle. Bring it closer and raise it up. Very nice, we can see. A little higher, and to the left.

So this is from 1992, in Nirala Nagar, at Shri Mataji's house?

Aunty: No, this wasn't at the house. She had come for a public program. You can see the tent. At that program, my mother-in-law saw Lord Vishnu.

Interviewer: So this photo is from when?

Aunty: 1992, at a public program. When Shri Mataji gave vibrations to everyone, one of the first things she asked was, "Has someone made a swastika?" We had made a large swastika on the ground where she was seated, far away. She said, "You have made a swastika, haven't you?" She knew everything that was in our minds. She is God, after all.

There were only about 30-35 people then. As soon as Shri Mataji did this [raises hands], our tent’s roof lifted up. Someone told me later, "You may not have realized it, but when Shri Mataji gave vibrations, the entire tent rose up." We had closed off the sides to manage the crowd, but when the crowd grew so large, she gave realization, and the whole tent lifted. This is recorded in a video from Lucknow.

Interviewer: Please email that to me, so we can add it to this video for others to see.

Uncle: Dr. Nigam had introduced her.

Aunty: Just as a towel can soak up water, Shri Mataji soaked up my entire fever.

Interviewer: Please share some more miracles.

Uncle: In '95, we had a program in Lucknow at the Railway Stadium. The first India-Pakistan match was played there. We booked it again for our program in '96. The tent provider backed out at the last minute. I wondered what to do. I took two other tent vendors with me and persuaded another one to help, promising him whatever he needed.

On the first day, nothing was ready, not even the generator. Shri Mataji's program was about to start, so I called Dr. Nigam and said, "Dr. Nigam, please stop Shri Mataji, the program is not ready, the dais is not ready!" He replied, "Dr. Jay Prakash, she has already left!"

Just then, Shri Mataji's car arrived. As her car's headlights shone on the stadium, the entire stadium lit up! Another miracle happened at the same time. A Sahaja Yogi from Banaras was walking with his bag, and the moment Shri Mataji's car lights fell, all the lights came on.

Mataji was walking, and I stood with folded hands, saying, "Mataji, you must be in great trouble. I will fix this by tomorrow." People were holding up her sari so her feet wouldn't get tangled. She said, "Why are you getting worried? You are getting troubled."

The next day, it took three people to manage everything. I called my own men and others.

[Shows another photo]

This is from '96. It was so well-known in Ganpatipule that Lucknow's program was fantastic. There was so much lightning, yet Shri Mataji had put flowers...

Interviewer: It's so wonderful that you have taken the trouble to take photos out of your albums and share them with us at this time.

Uncle: In '95, many miracles happened. Shri Mataji had said, "I have given realization to 100,000 Sahaja Yogis." We were in the room, and she said, "Let's go outside." When we went out, Dr. Nigam's sister was there, and Shri Mataji immediately said, "Today I have given realization to one lakh people."

After she left, there were so many fruits and flowers left. We got a phone call from her, asking us to send all the items to Prabhat's house, for Kalpana ji.

Interviewer: She also studied for some time at IT College, didn't she? Did she ever tell you about that when she was in Lucknow?

Uncle: She said she had studied in Lahore. Before that, perhaps she was at IT in Class 11.

Interviewer: Are there any other memories you would like to share?

Aunty: When she left for the last time, we were all crying. I had bought a ring to gift her from the collective donations. A jeweler was showing one for ₹12,000, then ₹11,000. I only had ₹10,000. He said, "Okay, ₹10,500." I said, "I won't give ₹500 more, I'll only give ₹10,000. Take it or leave it." So I got it for ₹10,000. She used to look at rings on her fingers, and my size is the same.

During the oti ceremony, Dr. Nigam told me to give the ring to her separately. At the station, when she was on the train, I gave it to her. She put it on and said, "Look, it is made exactly for my size!" It fit her perfectly.

Many people used to come to meet her, including many from her in-laws' side. Anup Srivastava’s family would come. Shri Mataji was very loving towards that family. Anup and his sister are in Australia now; Shri Mataji arranged both their marriages. His father was taken ill to Delhi. When he passed away, Shri Mataji told Anup's sister, "Go and tell your mother that he is sitting with me." Do you understand? After death, she took him into her protection and conveyed this message. Anup's mother came to our house; she was a very simple and gentle lady.

Interviewer: Shri Mataji used to make them sit very close to her when they came.

We have taken a technological leap today, and all of this has become possible. Uncle and Aunty, so many thanks. Thank you so much for taking out the time and taking photos from your albums to share with us. Shri Mataji's time in Lucknow is very special for all of us.

My father, who lived in America for 10 years, was not a Sahaja Yogi. When he saw Shri Mataji for the first time... he was so struck by the glow on her face. She must have been in her 70s then, but my father said there was such a glow that he came from the back of the room to the front just to see her better. He told me, "Your Mataji has such a glow on her face; I went closer just to see it."

What happened was amazing. "Amazing" is not a big enough word. She made everything possible and has kept us all under her blessings. Thank you so much. Thank you, Dr. Prakash and Dr. Veena.

Thank you, all friends. We are all gathered today because of Shri Mataji. Thank you.

Jai Shri Mataji.

Jai Shri Mataji.